To create an A-Frame Web VR environment that utilizes the data from the API `https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi`, you can encapsulate everything into a single HTML file with embedded CSS and JavaScript. Below is a complete example that incorporates A-Frame and fetches data from the API to set up the scene.

Here's how you can do it:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>A-Frame Web VR Environment</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; height: 100vh; background: #000; }
        #loader { color: white; font-size: 24px; position: absolute; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="loader">Loading...</div>
    <a-scene>
        <a-sky id="sky" color="#000"></a-sky>
        <a-entity id="box" geometry="primitive: box" material="color: #4CC3D9" position="0 1 -5"></a-entity>
        <a-entity id="text" position="0 2 -5" text="value: Loading...; color: #FFF"></a-entity>
        <a-entity camera look-controls position="0 1.6 0"></a-entity>
        <a-entity light="type: ambient; color: #888"></a-entity>
    </a-scene>

    <script>
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', async () => {
            try {
                const response = await fetch('https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi');
                const data = await response.json();

                // Populate the scene with data
                const sky = document.getElementById('sky');
                const box = document.getElementById('box');
                const text = document.getElementById('text');
                const loader = document.getElementById('loader');

                // Update the scene based on API response
                sky.setAttribute('color', data.skyColor || '#000'); // Update sky color
                box.setAttribute('material', `color: ${data.boxColor || '#4CC3D9'}`); // Update box color
                text.setAttribute('text', `value: ${data.message || 'Hello, VR!'}; color: #FFF`); // Update text
                loader.style.display = 'none'; // Hide loader
            } catch (error) {
                console.error('Error fetching data:', error);
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure**: The HTML includes a head for meta and script tags, and a body that contains an A-Frame scene.
2. **A-Frame Setup**: A basic A-Frame scene is created with a sky, a box, text, a camera, and ambient light.
3. **Loading Message**: A loading message is displayed while the data is being fetched.
4. **Fetching API Data**: Upon loading the document, a GET request is made to `https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi`. The data received is expected to have certain fields like `skyColor`, `boxColor`, and `message`. Update the A-Frame entities accordingly.
5. **Error Handling**: If there’s an error fetching the data, it is logged to the console.

### Customization:
- Ensure that the API returns the correct JSON structure as expected. Adjust the attributes in the code as required based on the actual structure of the API response.
- You can expand this to include more entities, events, or other custom interactions as needed.

Below is an example of a single HTML file that creates an A-Frame Web VR environment using a 64-character string received from the API `https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi`. The expected structure is a JSON containing this string, which is used to set the colors and positions of multiple objects in the scene.

### Complete HTML Code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>A-Frame Web VR Environment</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; height: 100vh; background: #000; }
        #loader { color: white; font-size: 24px; position: absolute; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="loader">Loading...</div>
    <a-scene>
        <a-sky id="sky" color="#000"></a-sky>
        <a-entity camera look-controls position="0 1.6 0"></a-entity>
        <a-entity light="type: ambient; color: #888"></a-entity>
        <a-entity id="scene-container"></a-entity> <!-- Container for dynamic objects -->
    </a-scene>

    <script>
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', async () => {
            try {
                const response = await fetch('https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi');
                const data = await response.json();
                const itemsString = data.string; // Expect the string field to be a 64 character string.

                if (!itemsString || itemsString.length !== 64) {
                    throw new Error('Invalid string format');
                }

                const loader = document.getElementById('loader');
                loader.style.display = 'none'; // Hide loader

                const sceneContainer = document.getElementById('scene-container');

                // Create boxes based on the characters in the string
                for (let i = 0; i < itemsString.length; i++) {
                    const char = itemsString.charAt(i);
                    const color = `#${((1 << 24) * Math.random() | 0).toString(16)}`; // Random color for demonstration
                    const positionX = (i % 8) - 4; // 8 boxes across
                    const positionY = Math.floor(i / 8); // Stacked rows
                    const positionZ = -5; // Fixed distance from camera

                    // Create a box for each character
                    const box = document.createElement('a-box');
                    box.setAttribute('position', `${positionX} ${positionY} ${positionZ}`);
                    box.setAttribute('color', color);
                    box.setAttribute('depth', '0.5');
                    box.setAttribute('height', '1');
                    box.setAttribute('width', '1');
                    sceneContainer.appendChild(box);
                }

            } catch (error) {
                console.error('Error fetching or processing data:', error);
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **Structure**: The file maintains a basic HTML structure with A-Frame and necessary styling.
- **API Call**: It fetches JSON data from the specified API URL and expects a JSON structure with the key `string` that holds a 64-character string.
- **String Validation**: It checks the length of the string; if it is not 64 characters, an error is thrown.
- **Dynamic Scene Creation**:
    - The script iterates over each character in the 64-character string.
    - For each character, it generates a colored box positioned in a grid layout (8 boxes per row).
    - Each box is given a random color to visually differentiate them.
- **Scene Composition**: The boxes are appended to a container entity `<a-entity id="scene-container"></a-entity>` within the A-Frame scene.
- **Error Handling**: Errors in fetching or processing the data are logged to the console for debugging.

### Note:
- Adjust the `color` assignment as needed to represent meaningful data from `itemsString` if needed.
- You can modify the layout and styling of the VR environment to fit your desired aesthetics or interactivity.

To create a Web VR environment that continuously updates every second with a new 64-character string from `https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi`, you can modify the previous example. This will include a function to fetch the data and update the positions and colors of the objects based on the latest string.

Below is the complete HTML code that fulfills this requirement:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>A-Frame Web VR Environment</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; height: 100vh; background: #000; }
        #loader { color: white; font-size: 24px; position: absolute; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="loader">Loading...</div>
    <a-scene>
        <a-sky id="sky" color="#000"></a-sky>
        <a-entity camera look-controls position="0 1.6 0"></a-entity>
        <a-entity light="type: ambient; color: #888"></a-entity>
        <a-entity id="scene-container"></a-entity> <!-- Container for dynamic objects -->
    </a-scene>

    <script>
        const container = document.getElementById('scene-container');
        const loader = document.getElementById('loader');

        // Function to fetch and update the scene with new objects
        async function fetchAndUpdateObjects() {
            try {
                const response = await fetch('https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi');
                const data = await response.json();
                const itemsString = data.string; // 64 character string

                if (!itemsString || itemsString.length !== 64) {
                    throw new Error('Invalid string format');
                }

                // Clear existing objects
                while (container.firstChild) {
                    container.removeChild(container.firstChild);
                }

                // Create boxes based on the characters in the string
                for (let i = 0; i < itemsString.length; i++) {
                    const char = itemsString.charAt(i);
                    const color = `#${((1 << 24) * Math.random() | 0).toString(16)}`; // Random color for demonstration
                    const positionX = (i % 8) - 4; // 8 boxes across
                    const positionY = Math.floor(i / 8); // Stacked rows
                    const positionZ = -5; // Fixed distance from camera

                    // Create a box for each character
                    const box = document.createElement('a-box');
                    box.setAttribute('position', `${positionX} ${positionY} ${positionZ}`);
                    box.setAttribute('color', color);
                    box.setAttribute('depth', '0.5');
                    box.setAttribute('height', '1');
                    box.setAttribute('width', '1');
                    container.appendChild(box);
                }

                loader.style.display = 'none'; // Hide loader after first load
            } catch (error) {
                console.error('Error fetching or processing data:', error);
            }
        }

        // Initial fetch
        fetchAndUpdateObjects();

        // Fetch and update every second
        setInterval(fetchAndUpdateObjects, 1000);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure**: The basic structure remains the same with an A-Frame environment and necessary styles.
2. **Container for Objects**: The `<a-entity id="scene-container"></a-entity>` is used as a dynamic container for the boxes that will be updated.
3. **Fetch and Update Function**:
   - The `fetchAndUpdateObjects()` function fetches the latest data from the API and processes the 64-character string.
   - If the string is valid, it clears any existing boxes from the container.
   - For each character in the string, it creates a new colored box positioned in a grid format and appends it to the container.
   - A random color is assigned to each box for visual variation.
4. **Continuous Update**:
   - `setInterval(fetchAndUpdateObjects, 1000);` is used to call the fetch function every second, updating the boxes' positions and colors continuously.
5. **Error Handling**: If fetching the data fails or the format is invalid, it logs the error to the console.

### Usage:
- This code can be saved as an HTML file and opened in a browser that supports Web VR (like Chrome with WebXR enabled) to see the updates every second based on the received data from the API.

To create a Web VR environment where characters from a string obtained from the API `https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi` are mapped to specific RGB color values based on predefined mappings, I'll demonstrate how to implement this in a single HTML file. 

This example will include:
- A predefined color mapping for the supported characters (a-z, A-Z, 0-9, hyphen `-`, and period `.`).
- A function to fetch the new character string every second.
- Updating the colors of the objects in the VR scene based on the fetched string.

Here's the complete HTML code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>DudeWorld VR</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; height: 100vh; background: #000; }
        #loader { color: white; font-size: 24px; position: absolute; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="loader">Loading...</div>
    <a-scene>
        <a-sky id="sky" color="#000"></a-sky>
        <a-entity camera look-controls position="0 1.6 0"></a-entity>
        <a-entity light="type: ambient; color: #888"></a-entity>
        <a-entity id="scene-container"></a-entity> <!-- Container for dynamic objects -->
    </a-scene>

    <script>
        const container = document.getElementById('scene-container');
        const loader = document.getElementById('loader');

        // Predefined color mapping
        const colorMap = {
            'a': 'rgb(255, 0, 0)',      'b': 'rgb(255, 127, 0)',  'c': 'rgb(255, 255, 0)',
            'd': 'rgb(0, 255, 0)',      'e': 'rgb(0, 0, 255)',    'f': 'rgb(75, 0, 130)',
            'g': 'rgb(148, 0, 211)',     'h': 'rgb(255, 20, 147)', 'i': 'rgb(255, 105, 180)',
            'j': 'rgb(220, 20, 60)',     'k': 'rgb(0, 255, 255)',  'l': 'rgb(255, 0, 255)',
            'm': 'rgb(192, 192, 192)',   'n': 'rgb(128, 128, 128)', 'o': 'rgb(0, 0, 128)',
            'p': 'rgb(0, 128, 0)',      'q': 'rgb(0, 0, 0)',      'r': 'rgb(255, 0, 0)',
            's': 'rgb(128, 0, 0)',      't': 'rgb(128, 128, 0)',  'u': 'rgb(0, 128, 128)',
            'v': 'rgb(0, 0, 255)',      'w': 'rgb(75, 0, 130)',   'x': 'rgb(255, 105, 180)',
            'y': 'rgb(255, 165, 0)',    'z': 'rgb(255, 20, 147)',
            'A': 'rgb(255, 255, 255)',  'B': 'rgb(200, 200, 200)', 'C': 'rgb(150, 150, 150)',
            'D': 'rgb(255, 215, 0)',    'E': 'rgb(255, 105, 180)', 'F': 'rgb(0, 0, 0)',
            'G': 'rgb(100, 100, 100)',   'H': 'rgb(255, 192, 203)', 'I': 'rgb(240, 128, 128)',
            'J': 'rgb(150, 75, 0)',      'K': 'rgb(205, 92, 92)',  'L': 'rgb(50, 205, 50)',
            'M': 'rgb(238, 130, 238)',   'N': 'rgb(255, 140, 0)',  'O': 'rgb(0, 0, 139)',
            'P': 'rgb(255, 218, 185)',   'Q': 'rgb(145, 105, 175)', 'R': 'rgb(255, 0, 127)',
            'S': 'rgb(70, 130, 180)',    'T': 'rgb(255, 20, 147)',  'U': 'rgb(127, 255, 0)',
            'V': 'rgb(252, 252, 252)',   'W': 'rgb(200, 0, 0)',     'X': 'rgb(0, 0, 200)',
            'Y': 'rgb(100, 100, 0)',      'Z': 'rgb(25, 25, 220)',
            '0': 'rgb(255, 255, 255)',   '1': 'rgb(0, 255, 0)',    '2': 'rgb(0, 0, 255)',
            '3': 'rgb(255, 0, 0)',       '4': 'rgb(255, 255, 0)',  '5': 'rgb(0, 255, 255)',
            '6': 'rgb(255, 20, 147)',    '7': 'rgb(255, 105, 180)', '8': 'rgb(220, 20, 60)',
            '9': 'rgb(0, 128, 128)',     '-': 'rgb(128, 0, 0)',    '.': 'rgb(50, 205, 50)'
        };

        // Function to fetch and update the scene with new objects
        async function fetchAndUpdateObjects() {
            try {
                const response = await fetch('https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi');
                const data = await response.json();
                const itemsString = data.string; // 64 character string

                if (!itemsString || itemsString.length !== 64) {
                    throw new Error('Invalid string format');
                }

                // Clear existing objects
                while (container.firstChild) {
                    container.removeChild(container.firstChild);
                }

                // Create boxes based on the characters in the string
                for (let i = 0; i < itemsString.length; i++) {
                    const char = itemsString.charAt(i);
                    const color = colorMap[char] || 'rgb(255, 255, 255)'; // Default to white if not found
                    const positionX = (i % 8) - 4; // 8 boxes across
                    const positionY = Math.floor(i / 8); // Stacked rows
                    const positionZ = -5; // Fixed distance from camera

                    // Create a box for each character
                    const box = document.createElement('a-box');
                    box.setAttribute('position', `${positionX} ${positionY} ${positionZ}`);
                    box.setAttribute('color', color);
                    box.setAttribute('depth', '0.5');
                    box.setAttribute('height', '1');
                    box.setAttribute('width', '1');
                    container.appendChild(box);
                }

                loader.style.display = 'none'; // Hide loader after first load
            } catch (error) {
                console.error('Error fetching or processing data:', error);
            }
        }

        // Initial fetch
        fetchAndUpdateObjects();

        // Fetch and update every second
        setInterval(fetchAndUpdateObjects, 1000);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **Color Mapping**: A predefined `colorMap` object is created to map each character (a-z, A-Z, 0-9, `-`, `.`) to specific RGB color values. Characters that don't match the mapping default to white.

2. **Scene Setup**: The A-Frame scene is set up with a sky, camera, ambient light, and a container (`scene-container`) for the objects.

3. **Fetching and Updating**:
   - The `fetchAndUpdateObjects` function retrieves the 64-character string from the API every second.
   - It creates and positions colored boxes in a grid layout according to the fetched string characters.
   - If a character isn't recognized (i.e., not in the mapping), it uses white as the default color.

4. **Automatic Updates**:
   - The `setInterval(fetchAndUpdateObjects, 1000)` function calls the update function every second to refresh the scene with new colors and positions.

### Usage: 
- Save the above code as an HTML file, open it in a suitable web browser that supports WebVR, and observe the dynamically updated 3D scene where the boxes change colors based on the newly fetched character string every second.

Here’s a complete HTML file that sets up a Web VR environment called "DudeWorld" with 10 random objects initially seeded in the scene. The objects will be random boxes with random colors placed at different positions. Additionally, this setup will still fetch a new 64-character string from the API every second for continuous updates.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>DudeWorld VR</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; height: 100vh; background: #000; }
        #loader { color: white; font-size: 24px; position: absolute; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="loader">Loading...</div>
    <a-scene>
        <a-sky id="sky" color="#000"></a-sky>
        <a-entity camera look-controls position="0 1.6 0"></a-entity>
        <a-entity light="type: ambient; color: #888"></a-entity>
        <a-entity id="scene-container"></a-entity> <!-- Container for dynamic objects -->
    </a-scene>

    <script>
        const container = document.getElementById('scene-container');
        const loader = document.getElementById('loader');

        // Predefined color mapping
        const colorMap = {
            'a': 'rgb(255, 0, 0)',      'b': 'rgb(255, 127, 0)',  'c': 'rgb(255, 255, 0)',
            'd': 'rgb(0, 255, 0)',      'e': 'rgb(0, 0, 255)',    'f': 'rgb(75, 0, 130)',
            'g': 'rgb(148, 0, 211)',     'h': 'rgb(255, 20, 147)', 'i': 'rgb(255, 105, 180)',
            'j': 'rgb(220, 20, 60)',     'k': 'rgb(0, 255, 255)',  'l': 'rgb(255, 0, 255)',
            'm': 'rgb(192, 192, 192)',   'n': 'rgb(128, 128, 128)', 'o': 'rgb(0, 0, 128)',
            'p': 'rgb(0, 128, 0)',      'q': 'rgb(0, 0, 0)',      'r': 'rgb(255, 0, 0)',
            's': 'rgb(128, 0, 0)',      't': 'rgb(128, 128, 0)',  'u': 'rgb(0, 128, 128)',
            'v': 'rgb(0, 0, 255)',      'w': 'rgb(75, 0, 130)',   'x': 'rgb(255, 105, 180)',
            'y': 'rgb(255, 165, 0)',    'z': 'rgb(255, 20, 147)',
            'A': 'rgb(255, 255, 255)',  'B': 'rgb(200, 200, 200)', 'C': 'rgb(150, 150, 150)',
            'D': 'rgb(255, 215, 0)',    'E': 'rgb(255, 105, 180)', 'F': 'rgb(0, 0, 0)',
            'G': 'rgb(100, 100, 100)',   'H': 'rgb(255, 192, 203)', 'I': 'rgb(240, 128, 128)',
            'J': 'rgb(150, 75, 0)',      'K': 'rgb(205, 92, 92)',  'L': 'rgb(50, 205, 50)',
            'M': 'rgb(238, 130, 238)',   'N': 'rgb(255, 140, 0)',  'O': 'rgb(0, 0, 139)',
            'P': 'rgb(255, 218, 185)',   'Q': 'rgb(145, 105, 175)', 'R': 'rgb(255, 0, 127)',
            'S': 'rgb(70, 130, 180)',    'T': 'rgb(255, 20, 147)',  'U': 'rgb(127, 255, 0)',
            'V': 'rgb(252, 252, 252)',   'W': 'rgb(200, 0, 0)',     'X': 'rgb(0, 0, 200)',
            'Y': 'rgb(100, 100, 0)',      'Z': 'rgb(25, 25, 220)',
            '0': 'rgb(255, 255, 255)',   '1': 'rgb(0, 255, 0)',    '2': 'rgb(0, 0, 255)',
            '3': 'rgb(255, 0, 0)',       '4': 'rgb(255, 255, 0)',  '5': 'rgb(0, 255, 255)',
            '6': 'rgb(255, 20, 147)',    '7': 'rgb(255, 105, 180)', '8': 'rgb(220, 20, 60)',
            '9': 'rgb(0, 128, 128)',     '-': 'rgb(128, 0, 0)',    '.': 'rgb(50, 205, 50)'
        };

        // Function to create random boxes
        function createRandomBox(index) {
            const box = document.createElement('a-box');
            box.setAttribute('position', `${(Math.random() * 10 - 5).toFixed(2)} ${(Math.random() * 5).toFixed(2)} ${(-5 - Math.random() * 5).toFixed(2)}`);
            box.setAttribute('color', `rgb(${Math.floor(Math.random() * 256)}, ${Math.floor(Math.random() * 256)}, ${Math.floor(Math.random() * 256)})`);
            box.setAttribute('depth', '0.5');
            box.setAttribute('height', '1');
            box.setAttribute('width', '1');
            return box;
        }

        // Function to fetch and update the scene with new objects
        async function fetchAndUpdateObjects() {
            try {
                const response = await fetch('https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi');
                const data = await response.json();
                const itemsString = data.string; // 64 character string

                if (!itemsString || itemsString.length !== 64) {
                    throw new Error('Invalid string format');
                }

                // Clear existing objects
                while (container.firstChild) {
                    container.removeChild(container.firstChild);
                }

                // Create random boxes
                for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
                    const box = createRandomBox(i);
                    container.appendChild(box);
                }

                // Create boxes based on the characters in the string
                for (let i = 0; i < itemsString.length; i++) {
                    const char = itemsString.charAt(i);
                    const color = colorMap[char] || 'rgb(255, 255, 255)'; // Default to white if not found
                    const positionX = (i % 8) - 4; // 8 boxes across
                    const positionY = Math.floor(i / 8); // Stacked rows
                    const positionZ = -5; // Fixed distance from camera

                    // Create a box for each character
                    const box = document.createElement('a-box');
                    box.setAttribute('position', `${positionX} ${positionY + 2} ${positionZ}`);
                    box.setAttribute('color', color);
                    box.setAttribute('depth', '0.5');
                    box.setAttribute('height', '1');
                    box.setAttribute('width', '1');
                    container.appendChild(box);
                }

                loader.style.display = 'none'; // Hide loader after first load
            } catch (error) {
                console.error('Error fetching or processing data:', error);
            }
        }

        // Initial random box creation
        for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            const box = createRandomBox(i);
            container.appendChild(box);
        }

        // Fetch and update every second
        setInterval(fetchAndUpdateObjects, 1000);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **Random Box Creation**: The function `createRandomBox(index)` generates a cube with a random position and a random color. The position is limited to a certain area in the VR space, ensuring the boxes don’t overlap excessively and are visible to the user.

2. **Initial Random Objects**: When the scene is first loaded, 10 random boxes are created and appended to the scene. This gives the user an immediate visual experience.

3. **Handling Incoming Data**: The `fetchAndUpdateObjects` function continues to fetch the 64-character string every second. If the string is valid, it generates and positions colored boxes based on the characters, as well as handling the random initialization of the boxes.

4. **Continuous Updates**: The random boxes created during the initial render will persist while new boxes from the string are added every second.

### Usage:
- Save the code as an HTML file and open it in a browser that supports Web VR to see it in action. The initial random boxes will appear immediately, and new object colors will update every second according to the fetched string.

To create a Web VR environment that displays the current JSON values fetched from `https://games.h4ks.com/game/dudeapi` and updates every second, we can modify the previous example code. Instead of just visualizing the values, we will also display them on the screen.

In this example, the continuous update of both the 3D scene and the displayed JSON data will be handled.

Here's the complete HTML code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>DudeWorld VR</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; height: 100vh; background: #000; position: relative; }
        #loader { color: white; font-size: 24px; position: absolute; }
        #json-data { position: absolute; top: 10px; left: 10px; color: white; font-size: 18px; background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7); padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="loader">Loading...</div>
    <div id="json-data">Fetching data...</div>
    <a-scene>
        <a-sky id="sky" color="#000"></a-sky>
        <a-entity camera look-controls position="0 1.6 0"></a-entity>
